om 1824 restructured as Russell & Company. By early 1831 had smuggled 3,500 chests of Indian opium into China — approximately twenty percent of the country's total annual opium imports that year. Russell & Company was the largest American opium trading house in China."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"Skull and Bones founded by his Russell cousin","body":"His second cousin William Huntington Russell co-founded Skull and Bones at Yale in 1832 with Alphonso Taft — both Hooker descendants themselves. The Russell family fortune that helped support the society's early decades had been substantially built on his own Russell & Company opium trading at Canton, China."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Business partner was FDR's maternal grandfather","body":"Among the partners at Russell & Company was Warren Delano Jr. — the maternal grandfather of President Franklin Delano Roosevelt. The Russell-Delano connection ran through the China opium trade two generations before Delano's grandson reached the White House."},{"number":4,"category":"architecture","header":"Greek Revival mansion 1828 by Ithiel Town","body":"On returning from Canton 1831 he commissioned a major Greek Revival mansion at Middletown CT, designed 1826-1828 by Ithiel Town — the same architect Daniel Wadsworth used for the Wadsworth Atheneum. The Middletown mansion remains a landmark of the Greek Revival movement in American domestic architecture."},{"number":5,"category":"marriage","header":"Lost his first wife at twenty-three, 1819","body":"Married Mary Cotton Osborn on 6 October 1815 in New York; she died in 1819 leaving him with two sons. Six years later in October 1825 he married her sister Frances Ann Osborn — the family stabilization pattern echoed in many Dwight cousins of his generation."}],"slug":"samuel-russell-1789"},"neighborhood":{"focus":{"id":"HD1371","slug":"samuel-russell-1789","n":"Samuel Wadsworth Russell","by":1789,"dy":1862,"sx":"m","hd":true,"td":false,"ee":false,"g":7}