ussell family homes along High Street Middletown are now part of the Wesleyan campus."},"INST022":{"id":"INST022","primary_name":"American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions","name":"American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions","alt_names":["ABCFM","American Board"],"type":"missionary_society","founding_year":1810,"location":{"city":"Boston","state":"Massachusetts"},"primary_persons":["X00724"],"hooker_connected_people":["X00724","X02121","X02122","T01213","H00527","I01195"],"person_ids":[],"related_institutions":[],"related_landmarks":[],"tags":["native_american_contact","missionary"],"sources":[{"short":"Wikipedia","note":"Elias Cornelius (clergyman); ABCFM"}],"notes":"First American foreign-mission organization. Tree connections: Rev. Elias Cornelius (agent 1816, secretary 1831-32); Ainsworth and Harriet Ellsworth Blunt, missionaries to the Cherokee at Brainerd, Tennessee; Eliza Talcott, missionary to Japan; Rev. William Banfield Capron, Madura mission; Judge John Hooker, member."}},"crossConnections":[{"type":"artifact","related_id":"HD1378","link_text":"Thomas Macdonough Russell Sr.","display_label":"His great-grandson donated the firm's Canton archive to the Library of Congress.","slug":"thomas-russell-sr-1874"},{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"HD1395","link_text":"William Huntington Russell","display_label":"Second cousins — both great-grandsons of Noadiah Russell. Russell co-founded Skull and Bones in 1832, the same year Samuel's Russell & Company reached its peak opium operation in Canton.","slug":"william-russell-1809"}]}